DPO (Direct Preference Optimization) and GRPO (Group Relative Policy Optimization) are both alignment methods for LLMs, but they differ fundamentally in how they learn from feedback:

DPO — Offline, Pairwise Preferences
Requires a static dataset of preference pairs: (chosen, rejected) for the same input
Eliminates the reward model entirely — optimizes the policy directly using a closed-form loss derived from the Bradley-Terry preference model
Training is offline: collect all preference data upfront, then train

Strength: simple pipeline (no reward model, no sampling at train time)

Weakness: needs high-quality human preference pairs; can't self-improve beyond what's in the dataset




GRPO — Online, Self-Generated Rewards

Generates multiple candidate outputs (a "group") from the current policy for each prompt
Scores each candidate using a reward signal (rule-based, verifier, or model-based)
Computes relative advantage within the group — no external baseline or critic model needed
Updates the policy toward higher-reward responses within each group

Training is online/iterative: the model improves by exploring and self-evaluating

Strength: doesn't need pre-collected preference pairs; naturally handles tasks with verifiable correctness (math, code, structured output)

Weakness: needs a reliable reward signal; more compute at train time (multiple rollouts per prompt)
For your use case (structured tax asset generation), DPO is a good fit because you already have human-corrected (preferred) vs raw LLM (non-preferred) pairs from the HITL pipeline. GRPO would be more appropriate if you had a programmatic verifier (e.g., schema validation, reference completeness check) and wanted the model to self-improve iteratively without human labels.





