How DPO learns from this:
DPO doesn't learn what to output for a specific document — it learns the style and quality patterns that distinguish preferred from non-preferred outputs. Across your 10 pairs, the model picks up signals like:
	• References should be populated (not empty) — reviewer flagged this as "material omission"
	• Client_Issue should be concise, tax-focused, anonymized (max 120 words per VX.X.10)
	• TaxProf_Analysis should be substantive (2-3 paragraphs), not transaction-driven
	• The structured JSON should prioritize RAG findability over verbatim extraction

The DPO loss function for each pair:
Increase log P(preferred | input) relative to log P(non_preferred | input)
Even though each source document is different, the model generalizes the correction patterns — it learns that human reviewers consistently prefer more tax-focused, properly structured, reference-complete outputs over raw o4-mini outputs.
With 10 pairs (8 train / 2 val), this is a very small dataset. It will nudge the model's behavior but won't dramatically reshape it. As more assets get reviewed (the 33 NULL rows), your dataset grows and the signal strengthens.

