GRPO - Group Relative Policy Optimization

Schema verification only catches structural issues (valid JSON, fields present). To improve content quality (tax relevance, analytical depth, proper anonymization), you need richer reward signals. Here's how GRPO applies to your asset pipeline:

The core idea: Generate multiple asset candidates for the same source document, score each on quality dimensions, then reinforce the better ones.

Quality reward components for your use case:

1. Reviewer Alignment Reward (learned from KH HITL data) Train a lightweight reward model on your existing review_comment data. The reviewer (Tijn) consistently evaluates along specific axes — you can extract scoring rubrics:

Tax-focus vs transaction-focus (the rejected asset was "too transaction-driven")
Statutory anchoring (citing specific legislation)
Analytical separation (clear structure between distinct tax issues)
RAG findability of Client_Issue

2. Source Faithfulness (NLI-based) Use a natural language inference model to score whether the generated asset is entailed by the source document — penalizes hallucination:

For each claim in TaxProf__Analysis, check if it's grounded in the source text
Reward = proportion of claims that are entailed
This directly addresses quality: the model learns not to fabricate legal references or invent tax positions

3. Semantic Distinctiveness Between Fields Your reviewer praised assets where fields have clear, non-overlapping roles. Score:

Client_Issue ≠ paraphrase of Asset (cosine distance > threshold → reward)
TaxProf_Analysis adds reasoning beyond what's in Asset (information gain → reward)
This teaches the model that each field has a distinct purpose

4. Reference Quality Reward The missing-references issue that caused rejection:

Extract legislation/regulation mentions from source doc (regex + entity recognition)
Compare to References field — reward for recall of statutory citations
Unlike schema check (non-empty list), this rewards correct and complete references

5. Conciseness vs Completeness Trade-off

Client_Issue: reward peaks at 80-120 words with high information density
TaxProf_Analysis: reward for covering all tax themes from source, penalize repetition
Measured via compression ratio (meaning per word)

For each source document:
  1. Generate 8 candidate asset outputs (rollouts)
  2. Score each with composite reward:
       R = 0.3 × faithfulness
         + 0.25 × reviewer_alignment  
         + 0.2 × reference_completeness
         + 0.15 × field_distinctiveness
         + 0.1 × conciseness
  3. Compute group-relative advantage (no external baseline needed)
  4. Update policy toward higher-reward candidates

Why this beats DPO alone for quality: DPO is limited to the existing preference pairs (51 rows). GRPO can generate thousands of training signals from the same source documents by exploring diverse outputs and scoring them. The model discovers quality patterns that humans haven't explicitly corrected yet — like "always cite the specific article number" or "separate WHT analysis from CIT analysis into distinct paragraphs."

Practical path for KH:

Start with DPO (you have the data now) — establishes a strong baseline
Build the reward model from review_comment data (even 51 comments teach meaningful patterns)
Layer GRPO on top — the model self-improves on quality dimensions which KH reviewer cares about

